1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] So my paper explores the impact of the Council of Nicaea on Maximus the Confessor's conception of the Logos as Christian formal principle.

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] Prior to Nicaea, it was still possible, in originist fashion, to speak of a first god and a second god.

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:21,000
[SPEAKER_00] The father is God himself, Alto Theos, and the Logos is simply God, Theos.

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] This enabled some theologians to safeguard the simplicity of the one God,

5
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] while relegating the formal content of the divine mind to the subordinate Logos as a unity and multiplicity.

6
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] After Nicaea, this kind of hierarchical approach to the problem of unity and multiplicity is no longer possible.

7
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] The Logos is declared homo usios with the father,

8
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] and this marks an irreversible break with the Platonic model of mediated terms.

9
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] While the Cappadocians are largely silent on the topic of the ideas,

10
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] St. Maximus embarks upon a daring retrieval of Origen's Logos theology,

11
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] simultaneously restoring the Logos as Christian formal principle,

12
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] while bringing it in line with the consubstantiality proclaimed by Nicaea.

13
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] The result is a divine Logos paradoxically at once, transcendently one and many.

14
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] Joining Pauline Ecclesiology to Porphyrian logic,

15
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] Maximus offers a new model of unity and multiplicity.

16
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] The One Logos is not a radical simplicity in line with the Neoplatonic One,

17
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] but the fullness of wisdom recapitulating all things in his unifying embrace.

18
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] So needless to say, this isn't a Christianity against the philosophers.

19
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's in many ways a different philosophical approach,

20
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] which of course has a theological foundation.

21
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] So as Davis notes in his book on the Seven Ecumenical Councils,

22
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] he says, "The problem which would confront the bishops of Nicaea

23
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] had long been a basic question confronting previous Christian theologians.

24
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] It was not simply whether Jesus is God.

25
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] The problem was how within a monotheistic system which the Church inherited from the Jews,

26
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] it was still possible to maintain the unity of God

27
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] while insisting on the deity of the One who was distinct from God the Father."

28
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] Among those who proffered a solution to this dilemma,

29
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] David singles out Origen as a potential source for the subordinationism of Arius.

30
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] While Arius arguably goes beyond Origen in calling the Logos a creature,

31
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] and insisting that there was when he was not,

32
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] he does share with Origen a fundamental assumption, and that is of mediation.

33
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] Just as Origen posits the Logos as a mediator between the absolute oneness of God

34
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] and the multiplicity of creation,

35
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:44,000
[SPEAKER_00] so Arius insists that the creative act of the transcendent deity

36
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] requires an instrument of creation, Christ the Logos,

37
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] through whom to mediate his creative power.

38
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] While the remnants of Arius's writings are fragmentary,

39
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:58,000
[SPEAKER_00] it's evident that the theological problem of subordinationism

40
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] is inseparable from the philosophical problem of mediation.

41
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] In terms of the former,

42
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] Yeroslav Pelikan points to the centrality of Proverbs 8:22-23,

43
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] "The Lord created me, and before the ages he established me,"

44
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] as key passages amenable to subordinationist reading.

45
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] Among the extant writings,

46
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] Arius in his letter to Eusebius comments on this verse that,

47
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] "Before he, the Logos, was begotten, or created, or ordained, or established,

48
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] he did not exist."

49
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] Elsewhere, it is said of the origins that,

50
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] "They maintain that Christ is a creature because of what is written in Proverbs 8:22."

51
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] Yet, as Pelikan notes with acuity, the exegist of Proverbs emerges, as he says,

52
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] "in the light of a particular set of theological a prioris

53
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] which produced the Aryan doctrine of Christ as creature."

54
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] To this, I would add only that these theological a prioris

55
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] owe much to the philosophical presuppositions of Platonic philosophy.

56
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] These a prioris, which Pelikan notes and which I intend to focus on here,

57
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] are summed up in the singular problem of mediation,

58
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] of bridging the gap between the one and the many.

59
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, given the constraints of time

60
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] and the fact that I want to focus a portion of this limited time on St. Maximus,

61
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] I offer an extremely abridged treatment of the problem of mediation in Aries

62
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] and its philosophical and theological milieu.

63
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] The starting point is the Aryan insistence upon the oneness of God.

64
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] According to our sources, the Aryans refer to God as monad

65
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] and superlatively as without beginning and most one,

66
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] from this monad emerged the dyad of the sun and the triad of the spirit

67
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] as derivative terms and not co-eternal with the monad.

68
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] The radical transcendence of Aries as God excluded the possibility

69
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] of any kind of consubstantiality with the sun and the spirit,

70
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] at risk of introducing composition, divisibility, and mutability into the divine being.

71
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] While Pelican refers to this as a starkly monotheistic view,

72
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] it is one that is central to the Greek philosophical tradition as well.

73
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] Plotinus, for example, insists upon the simplicity of one for precisely the same reason,

74
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] namely that plurality equals composition and composition equals dependency,

75
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:29,000
[SPEAKER_00] and this undermines the self-sufficiency of the first principle.

76
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] For everything depends upon it, while it depends upon nothing.

77
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now this transcendence creates a chasm between the one God and the multiplicity of creation.

78
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:44,000
[SPEAKER_00] On the one hand, the simplicity of God forbids any involvement with the world of becoming.

79
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:49,000
[SPEAKER_00] On the other hand, Aries maintained that the fragility of creatures, quote,

80
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] could not endure to be made by the absolute hand of the unoriginate.

81
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] A mediator was thus required, and Aries finds this in Christ the Logos,

82
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] as the instrument through whom the solitary God creates the world.

83
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] And here we return to Proverbs 8:23.

84
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] Though also created, the Logos is unlike other creatures in his primeval origins.

85
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] He was established, as we read, before the age as the principle of creation of his ways

86
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] for the sake of his works, Proverbs.

87
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] So as a kind of created God, the Logos stands midway between the uncreated and the created,

88
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] the radically simple and the manifold.

89
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] And it's not difficult, in my opinion, to see that Aries' interpretive scripture,

90
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] if not indebted, certainly parallels one of the most basic Platonic presuppositions.

91
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] Plato's Demiage II in the Timaeus delegates the creation of mortal men to the created immortal gods.

92
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's a very similar kind of dynamic, that the absolute has to create a kind of created deity

93
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] to create the mortal beings.

94
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] So this philosophical a priori in Aries finds a much fuller development

95
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] in his much more influential predecessor, Origen.

96
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] While it remains a matter of interpretation whether or not Origen deserves the title of subordinationist,

97
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] his understanding of the Logos is profoundly affected by the philosophical problem of mediation.

98
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] A striking example of this are his references to a first and second god,

99
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] which occur in both his Contra Calcium and his commentary on John.

100
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:36,000
[SPEAKER_00] Reminiscent of Aries, Origen states in Contra Calcium that it is incorrect to attribute work to the first god, the Proton Theon,

101
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] though one may do so allegorically to the second god, Ton Devturon.

102
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] As Origen explains, the first god gives the orders, while the second god, the Logos, carries them out as the instrument of creation.

103
00:07:51,000 --> 00:08:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] This two-fold designation follows that of the second century Platonist Numenius, who speaks of the Protos Theos as a simple, self-directed and free of all labors,

104
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] while the second god, the Demiurgos, is tasked with the work of creation.

105
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] Similarly, in commentary on John, Origen echoes Numenius, referring to the first god as god in himself, Autotheos,

106
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] and the second as simply god, Theos.

107
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, Numenius actually has the good in himself and the good, the Agathos, you know, Auto Agathos, Autotheos, but it's an interesting echo.

108
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] So as with Aries, Origen's one god remains aloof, unsullied by any active involvement with the world,

109
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] while the second god, the Demiurgic Logos, performs the work of creation under the lofty supervision of the first.

110
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] Origen's two-fold distinction plays a key role in mediating between the one and the many.

111
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] Like his philosophical and theological counterparts, Origen too understands God, the Protos Theos,

112
00:08:53,000 --> 00:09:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] as a simple intellectual being whom he terms monas and henas, free of all composition or addition.

113
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] It is Christ, the word and wisdom of God, whom Origen attributes the multiplicity of the ideas,

114
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] the outlines, prefigurations, and narrationes of creation.

115
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] It is interesting to note in this regard that Origen too invokes Proverbs 8:23,

116
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] though in contrast to Aries, Origen interprets wisdom as created and as the beginning of the ways of God,

117
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] as referring to wisdom, not to wisdom per se, but to the formal content of wisdom,

118
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] the createdness of the intelligible world according to which the Logos brings a sensible world into existence.

119
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] So Aries seems to attribute this createdness to the Logos himself,

120
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] whereas Origen seems to say no, the Logos is eternal,

121
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] but the ideas are what's being referred to as created, the ideas in the mind of the Logos.

122
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:49,000
[SPEAKER_00] So there's a bit of a softening there of the position, I think.

123
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] In the Contra-Calcum, Origen further reveals his hierarchical understanding of deity,

124
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] referring to the Logos as the being of beings and a second God,

125
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] while suggesting in the words of Plato himself that God the Father transcends being in rank and power.

126
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] There's something again, he doesn't quite go there,

127
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] but there's something reminiscent of Plotinus of the One in the noose a little bit.

128
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] Origen doesn't really develop that idea in full, I don't believe that he does.

129
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:21,000
[SPEAKER_00] So like the condemned Aries and the pagan Plotinus then,

130
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] Origen insists upon the radical transcendence and simplicity of the One,

131
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] while relegating the multiplicity of the intelligible world to a secondary principle, namely the Logos.

132
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] While Origen's condemnation occurred as late as the Council of Constantinople II and 553,

133
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:45,000
[SPEAKER_00] and there his alleged subordinationism only indirectly censured in the Christology of Evagrius,

134
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] his influence is often assumed in Aries' subordination condemned at Nicaea I.

135
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] Whether or not this is a fair estimation, and there is some suggestion maybe it's not,

136
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] The Credo's statements of Nicaea nonetheless definitively shut the door on any kind of hierarchical mediation typical of Hellenic philosophy.

137
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] In other words, though Origen is not explicitly the target of Nicaea,

138
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] after the proclamation of the Homo Ucyon in 325,

139
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] it is no longer possible for theologians to conceive of Christ the Logos in Platonic terms

140
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] as mediating between God and creation, the one and the many.

141
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's scarcely an accident of history that the Logos as an object of sustained theological inquiry

142
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] is conspicuously absent in the period following Nicaea,

143
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:36,000
[SPEAKER_00] and is revived only by St. Maximus in the 7th century.

144
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, this brings us to St. Maximus.

145
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] It is with Maximus that we encountered a renewed preoccupation with the Logos,

146
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] and a robust engagement with the problem of unity and multiplicity.

147
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] While the condemnation of Origen just one century prior exerts an influence in Maximus' Logos theology,

148
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] it is above all the rejection of subordinationism in the person of Arius

149
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] from the proclamation of the consubstantiality of the Father and the Son at Nicaea that is of primary importance.

150
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] In light of Nicaea, Maximus sets himself the unenviable task of reconciling the one and the many

151
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:21,000
[SPEAKER_00] without recourse to the principle of hierarchical mediation.

152
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] The consubstantiality of wisdom requires a fundamental rethinking of ancient assumptions

153
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] regarding the nature of both unity and multiplicity,

154
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] culminating in what I call Maximus' ecclesial cosmology.

155
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] To begin with, it's crucial to note, as one would expect,

156
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] that Maximus understands the Logos in accordance with Nicaea

157
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] as fully consubstantial with the Father, calling him, quote,

158
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] "the essential and substantial Logos of God the Father."

159
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] More strikingly, Maximus refers to the Logos in the very apophatic terms

160
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] typically reserved for the Neoplatonic One, calling him, quote,

161
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] "beyond being" , while denying that anything, apophatically speaking,

162
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] can be affirmed or attributed to the Logos.

163
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] As Homoousios, the Logos' Son shares the very same transcendent simplicity of the Father

164
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] on par with the Neoplatonic One.

165
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] And yet, cataphatically speaking,

166
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] that is, in the positive terms, Maximus simultaneously affirms that the Logos is manifold.

167
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] For the one Logos, as he says, is many Logi, and the many are one.

168
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] From all eternity, Maximus says further, the Logos, quote,

169
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] "contained within himself the preexistent Logi of created beings,

170
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] according to which he formed out of nothing the substance of the visible and invisible worlds."

171
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] So here we have, in a way, a return of these originist durationes, which is just Logi in Latin,

172
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] and yet somehow they're one.

173
00:13:54,000 --> 00:14:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] You know, this isn't a subordinate Logos, this isn't a noose, this is something on the level of the simplicity of the One.

174
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, to the troublesome passage of Proverbs 8, Maximus prefers Colossians 1:16,

175
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] "All things were created from him, through him, and returned unto him."

176
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] The fact that Maximus allows for a kind of multiplicity within the One God marks a striking departure from his pagan and Christian predecessors.

177
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] For Origen, Arius, and Plotinus, the One is radically simple,

178
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] and is only on the lower level of nous, or subordinate Logos, that a unity and multiplicity is affirmed.

179
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] Yet how is this possible?

180
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] How can the Logos be simultaneously one and many, at once simple and complex, without one aspect compromising the other?

181
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:49,000
[SPEAKER_00] How does Maximus resolve this antinomy?

182
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] He does so by combining the Christian understanding of the Church as a single body composed of many members,

183
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] with the logical categories of the Neopatonic philosopher Porphyry.

184
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] The ecclesial character of Maximus' Logos emerges within the context of his refutation of the originist notion of a pre-existent henad of rational beings.

185
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] Time does not allow me to elaborate upon this further here.

186
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] The crucial point is that this heretical doctrine had been foisted upon Gregory Nazianzus,

187
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] whose reference to beings as portions of God were being interpreted as referring to these pre-existent intellects or logica.

188
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] It is in defense of St. Gregory that Maximus ultimately presents his own transformed understanding of the Logos as simultaneously one and many.

189
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] Indeed, when Maximus says the one Logos is the many Logi and the many are one,

190
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] he is already pointing to the ecclesial character of the Logos.

191
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] As with origin, these Logi represent the prefigurations or predeterminations for creation,

192
00:15:52,000 --> 00:15:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] God's eternal intentions for beings created in time.

193
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:58,000
[SPEAKER_00] As such, says Maximus,

194
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] A Logos preceded the creation of everything,

195
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] Pantos,

196
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] that has received as being from God.

197
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] Evoking Ephesians 1:10,

198
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] Maximus states that all things,

199
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] the Panta,

200
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] are recapitulated in the one Logos,

201
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] insofar as they have their origin in him,

202
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] and all their diverse existences to him.

203
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] And it's this, Maximus argues,

204
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] that St. Gregory was referring to as portions of God.

205
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] All beings are portions of God,

206
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] insofar as their being corresponds to a particular Logos within the divine mind,

207
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] according to which they were created.

208
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] The whole of temporal creation is, as it were,

209
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] eternally grounded in the word and wisdom of God.

210
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] The ecclesial character of the Logos is one many is made explicit

211
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:49,000
[SPEAKER_00] when Maximus insists later in Ambiguum 7

212
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] that St. Gregory's reference to portions of God,

213
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] mire theu,

214
00:16:54,000 --> 00:16:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] is equivalent to members of God,

215
00:16:57,000 --> 00:16:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] meli theu.

216
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] Maximus argues,

217
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] For if a member, melos, is a part of the body,

218
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] and a part, meros, is the same as a portion,

219
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] miran,

220
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] then member, melos, and portion,

221
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] miran, are one and the same thing.

222
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] I find that very interesting and somewhat convoluted.

223
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:21,000
[SPEAKER_00] So to be portions of God, then,

224
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] Maximus is saying,

225
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] is to be members of the body of Christ.

226
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] Not merely, I argue, in the historical and ecclesial sense,

227
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] but in a timeless ontological and cosmological sense.

228
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:36,000
[SPEAKER_00] Ontologically speaking,

229
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] the whole of creation already exists as the body of Christ,

230
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] as a kind of cosmic ecclesia,

231
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] both transcendently, as ideas in the mind of God, as it were,

232
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] and imminently as the instantiation of those ideas within creation.

233
00:17:53,000 --> 00:17:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] All things are recapitulated, as Maximus likes to say,

234
00:17:56,000 --> 00:17:58,000
[SPEAKER_00] in Christ from the very beginning of the church,

235
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] from the very beginning,

236
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] as the church of the many logi,

237
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] with the one logos as the unifying principle or head.

238
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] Just as the diverse members of the historical church are united in their shared confession of the faith,

239
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] for they are of one heart and one mind,

240
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] so the many logi and the beings created according to the logi

241
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] are one in light of their common origin in their singular reference to the one logos,

242
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] the all-encompassing wisdom which contains everything in its intuitive embrace.

243
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] For this reason, in the mystagogy,

244
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] Maximus refers to the cosmos as, quote,

245
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] "a church made without hands."

246
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] Just as the church is comprised of sanctuary and nave,

247
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] and yet these two form a unified whole,

248
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] so the universe consists of the intelligible and sensible realms united without confusion,

249
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] asin hitos.

250
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] Each of these realms in turn represent a unity in multiplicity,

251
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] insofar as they too are wholes comprised of a diversity of parts.

252
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] And yet this entire diversity of creation, says Maximus,

253
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] is made one, quote,

254
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] by the reference to and oneness with God as their cause and beginning and end.

255
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] This oneness, Maximus makes clear,

256
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:21,000
[SPEAKER_00] does not involve the destruction of multiplicity.

257
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] Rather, he says that unity, quote,

258
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] "surpasses and outshines multiplicity like the sun outshining the stars."

259
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] The dazzling array of stars do not cease to exist in the light of dawn.

260
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] They simply become invisible in the presence of an infinitely greater light.

261
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] Similarly, when we glimpse the fundamental unity at the heart of reality,

262
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] multiplicity becomes relativized.

263
00:19:46,000 --> 00:19:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] This does not mean that multiplicity is thereby devalued.

264
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] and it means, in fact, that multiplicity is seen and understood from the higher vantage point of the one.

265
00:19:57,000 --> 00:20:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] This transcendent perspective, in fact, perfects multiplicity by rendering it integral, harmonious, and whole.

266
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] In a way, it elevates multiplicity.

267
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] Instead of just seeing, you know, that's just a tree, that's a person, that's a that,

268
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] and you see that everything's part of a grand totality, which in a way, I think, actually elevates particularity within the one.

269
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, in Ambigl 41, Maximus expresses a similar idea in the more abstract language of Porphyrian logic.

270
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:36,000
[SPEAKER_00] In his Ishigogi, or Introduction to Aristotelian logic, Porphyry explains how every genus and species unifies particulars,

271
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] while particulars divide and multiply.

272
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] So Porphyry says, "For species, and still more genera, gather the many items into a single nature,

273
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] whereas the particulars, or singulars in contrary fashion, always divide the one into plurality.

274
00:20:54,000 --> 00:21:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] For by sharing in the species, the many men are one man, and by the particulars, the one and common man is several.

275
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] For the singular is always divisive, whereas the common is collective and unifying."

276
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] So as genus, humanity is one.

277
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] As individuals, humanity is many.

278
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] Maximus echoes this very same logic when he states that,

279
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] "All things that are distinguished from each other by virtue of their individual differences

280
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] are generically united by universal and common identities,

281
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] and they are drawn together to one and the same by means of a certain generic logos of nature."

282
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] So just as individual beings are united with their common species,

283
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] while manifold species are made one within a shared genus,

284
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:45,000
[SPEAKER_00] so the many genera are joined together within a single overarching genus.

285
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] strictly speaking, a genus is not divided up by the species and particulars which are subsumed within it.

286
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] For no matter how many species of being or individual beings there might be,

287
00:21:56,000 --> 00:22:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] the genus being remains unchanged.

288
00:22:01,000 --> 00:22:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] In this way, a genus naturally unifies the diversity which proceeds from it.

289
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] At the same time, the genus is wholly and indivisibly present within that diversity.

290
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] For the diversity of beings are simply the increasing specification of universal being.

291
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] Nor are particulars annulled by their progressive enfoldment within their respective species and genera.

292
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] The eight billion human beings inhabiting this earth are not negated by the fact that they all belong to the common genus humanity,

293
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] while the genus humanity remains one, even as the world's population continues to expand.

294
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] Two minutes, huh?

295
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] Maximus sometimes explains this in the language of expansion and contraction.

296
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] The one genus expands in the multiplicity of genera, species, and particulars,

297
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] and the many particulars contract into species genera and the most generic genus.

298
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] Ultimately, says Maximus, it's the one logos who unites genus, species, and particulars.

299
00:22:56,000 --> 00:23:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] He says, "The logi of whatever is separated in particular are, as they say, contained by the logi of what is universal and generic,

300
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] and the more generic and universal logi are held together by wisdom, Sophia."

301
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] This wisdom, Maximus is clear, is none other than the word and wisdom of God,

302
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] who holds the diversity of creation within his unifying embrace.

303
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:21,000
[SPEAKER_00] Like the center and circumference of a circle, the logos is both the singular source of multiplicity

304
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] and the expansive embrace which limits, circumscribes, and preserves the many in an unconfused union.

305
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] So this porphyrian model, I think, shows how the many logi are embraced within the one logos

306
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] in a kind of logical hierarchy which simultaneously safeguards unity in its progressive unfolding into multiplicity,

307
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] while preserving multiplicity in its progressive n-folding into unity.

308
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:49,000
[SPEAKER_00] The one logos is the many logi and the many are one.

309
00:23:49,000 --> 00:23:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] This logical model parallels the ecclesial model which emphasizes how the multiplicity of creatures are all one in their singular origin in the one logos,

310
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] for the many logi are simply the elaboration of a single logos, God's singular overarching intention for the whole of creation.

311
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] Together, the porphyrian and ecclesial models articulate a new conception of unity and multiplicity as two poles of a single reality,

312
00:24:13,000 --> 00:24:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] rather than two realities hypostatically segregated from each other.

313
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] So to conclude, this fundamental rethinking of the problem of the one and the many stems directly from the consubstantiality of wisdom proclaimed at Nicaea.

314
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] For Maximus, the one logos is not a radical simplicity in line with the Neoplatonic one,

315
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] but the fullness of wisdom recapitulating all things in his unifying embrace.

316
00:24:37,000 --> 00:24:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] This leads both to a richer conception of the one as fullness rather than singularity,

317
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] and a more optimistic evaluation of multiplicity as an expression of the all-embracing unity of the Godhead.

318
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] Creation is not a fall or declension of being, but the radiant display of divine wisdom, in a word, theophany.

319
00:24:55,000 --> 00:25:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] So what then mediates between the Trinitarian God, whom Maximus calls the trihypostatic monad,

320
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] and the multiplicity of creation?

321
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] In brief, the logos himself, homoousios with the Father according to his divinity,

322
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] and homoousios with us according to his humanity,

323
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] creates the world immediately by means of a kind of cosmic incarnation.

324
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] Simultaneously transcendent and imminent, the logos himself, fully one, fully many,

325
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] bridges the chasm between creator and creation.

326
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] Thanks.

327
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] applause

